# SIDE QUEST — "The Great Objection"  (requires sq.the_complaints)
# The Complaint — the man who has lodged grievances at the afterlife's never-staffed desk for an age —
# follows you to the Court, where, for the first time, the desk is staffed: the powers convened, the
# management present. His thousand petty complaints were always one indictment. The one he can't write is
# Wrenna: his eleven-year-old daughter, walled for the crime of thinking. Now someone has to receive it.
class: ComplaintSideQuestContent

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# "The Great Objection" — deliver an age of grievances to the one desk that's finally staffed.
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
conversation: sq.complaint.objection | The Great Objection
node: 0 | The Complaint
  *(He is here. The Complaint — the fussy, persistent man who has shuffled his grievances through every era you've crossed, demanding a desk that was never staffed — stands at the very threshold of the Court of the Dead, and for the first time in an age, his hands are shaking. Because the desk, here, is *staffed.* The powers are convened. The management, such as it is, is *present.* He clutches his enormous sheaf — a lifetime, a death-time, of formal objections — and he looks at you with the terror of a man who has waited so long to be heard that being heard has become the thing he fears most.)* It's — they're *here.* *(barely a whisper.)* The desk. After all this — it's *staffed.* *(he grips the papers white-knuckled.)* And I find I — I've *rehearsed* this for an *age*, and now I'm — would you — *(he steadies, just.)* Would you *stand* with me while I *file* it? The objection. *All* of it. I don't think I can *do* it *alone.* Not now that there's finally *someone* to *do* it *to.*
  enter: SET sq.complaint_objection_begun
  auto: 1
node: 1 | The Complaint
  *(He spreads the sheaf — and you see it whole for the first time: not the rantings of a crank, but an *archive.* Dated. Itemized. An age of the afterlife's cruelties, formally objected to, one grievance at a time.)* Here it *all* is. *(his voice firms, the lifelong objector finding his footing.)* Every injustice of the *machine*, *recorded*, *dated*, *witnessed* by the *one* soul who *refused* to *accept* it. *(he turns the pages.)* The *queue* with no numbers. The *forms* with no field for *grief.* The *staff* who never *came.* The *Wall*, with *no appeals process*, *no consent*, *no exit interview.* *(his hand stops on a page near the bottom, in a different hand — older, shakier, written and rewritten.)* And — *(his voice drops)* — *this* one. The *one* under all the *others.* *(he doesn't read it aloud.)* You *know* what it *is.* *Wrenna.* My *girl.* *Eleven.* *Walled* for *thinking.* The *complaint* I could *never* *write* because it's *too big*, so I *wrote* a *thousand* *small* ones *instead*, to *hold* the *one* I *couldn't.* *(he looks up at the staffed desk, then at you, terrified.)* And *now* there's *someone* to *file* it *to.* The *thing* I *wanted* for an *age* — and I'm *afraid*, because *filing* it means they might *answer*, and an *answer* might be *worse* than the *silence.* *(he meets your eyes.)* Help me. *How* do I *file* a *lifetime's* *objection* — and the *one* grievance it was *always* *hiding* — at the *one* desk that *finally* *has* to *receive* it?
  * [INSIGHT 18] "You've spent an age believing the thousand petty complaints were a way to *hold* the one you couldn't write. But they were never a hiding place — they were the *case.* An age of dated, witnessed cruelties, building, grievance by grievance, to a single charge the machine can't dismiss as one grieving father. File them as what they always were: not complaints. An *indictment.*" -> indictment ?? falter
  * "Don't file the thousand first. File *Wrenna* first. Walk to the staffed desk, set down the one grievance that matters, and make them receive *her* — by name, eleven years old, walled for thinking — before a single word about queues or forms. The petty ones were the scaffolding. Wrenna is the building." -> wrenna
  * "The thing you actually want isn't an *answer* — it's an *acknowledgment.* For an age you've demanded the universe *receive*, in writing, the fact that someone *objected.* So make them *stamp* it. Not 'here is why we did it' — just 'received.' The cosmos formally admitting that the wrong was *witnessed* and *protested.* That's the win. That's all it ever was." -> received | fx SET sq.objection_formally_received
  * "You're afraid the answer is worse than the silence. So let me ask it *for* you. You shouldn't have to be the one who hears why your daughter was walled. Hand me the page. I'll stand at the desk and ask them why for Wrenna, and you can be a father grieving instead of a clerk filing." -> ask_for_him | if act5.ask_them_why
node: indictment | The Complaint
  *(He goes very still, staring at the sheaf as though seeing it for the first time.)* ...An indictment. *(slowly.)* Not complaints. *(he turns the dated pages with new eyes.)* I've *called* myself a *crank* for so *long* — *"the fussy dead man, the one who won't settle"* — that I *believed* it. I thought the *thousand* grievances were my *madness*, my *coping*, a *wall* of *paper* I built so I'd never have to *file* the *one* about *Wrenna.* *(his voice strengthens.)* But you're *right.* *Look* at them. *Dated.* *Itemized.* *Witnessed.* An *age* of the *machine's* *cruelties*, *recorded* by the *one* soul who *refused* to *call* them *fate.* *(he stands straighter.)* That's not a *crank's* *scribblings.* That's a *case.* The *prosecution* of the *whole* afterlife, *built* grievance by grievance, *years* in the *making*, *every* page a *charge* the *machine* *cannot* dismiss as *one* grieving *father* — because it's *not* one *father*, it's *the entire pattern*, *documented*, *the queue and the forms and the absent staff and the Wall*, all of it, *proof* that the *cruelty* is *systemic* and *witnessed* and *objected to.* *(he meets your eyes, transformed.)* I'm not a *crank.* I'm the *prosecutor* the *afterlife* never *knew* it had. *(fierce.)* File them as an *indictment.* All of them. And when the *machine* says *"these are the ravings of one bitter soul,"* I will *say*: *"No. These are an age of witnessed crimes, dated and filed by the one objector who would not accept that cruelty is the same as fate. Receive the indictment. You have no answer to a thing this thorough."* *(he gathers the sheaf with pride.)* Stand with me. Let's *file* the *case* I spent an *afterlife* *building* and *never* *knew* I was *building.*
  enter: SET sq.objection_indictment, SET act5.the_great_objection, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.garrow +5
  auto: 2
node: wrenna | The Complaint
  *(His hands tremble, and he looks at the one page — the oldest, the most rewritten — and then at the staffed desk, and his whole body resists.)* File Wrenna *first.* *(barely a whisper.)* Before the queues. Before the forms. *(he swallows.)* I've *always* filed her *last* — *buried* under the *thousand* *petty* ones — because *first* felt like — like *exposing* her, *naming* her, *making* her the *whole* point, and if she's the *whole* point and they *dismiss* her, then — *(his voice breaks.)* But you're saying the *petty* ones were *scaffolding.* *Wrenna* is the *building.* *(slowly, he lifts the one page free of the sheaf.)* You're *right.* I've been *protecting* her by *hiding* her, the way I *protect* the *grief* by *filing* it *small* — and *protecting* her has meant *no one* ever *had* to *look* at *her*, *Wrenna*, *eleven*, *walled* for *thinking*, *first*, *plainly*, *before* any *bureaucratic* *throat-clearing.* *(he holds the page like it's made of glass.)* So I'll walk to the *desk*, and I'll set *her* down *first*, and I'll *say* it *plain*: *"Before any other grievance — this. My daughter. Wrenna. Eleven years old. Clever, the way bright children are clever, which means she doubted, which you called a crime, and you walled her, and I want her name received first, before your queues and your forms, because she was first. She was always first. She was the whole reason I ever came to your wretched desk."* *(he meets your eyes, terrified and resolved.)* Stand with me. The *thousand* can *wait.* *Wrenna* has *waited* *long* enough to be *first.*
  enter: SET sq.objection_wrenna_first, SET act5.ask_them_why, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.naeve +6
  auto: 2
node: received | The Complaint
  *(Something eases in his frightened face — the relief of a man finally understanding what he's been fighting for.)* An *acknowledgment.* Not an *answer.* *(quietly.)* ...That's — *(he exhales, an age of breath.)* You've *named* the thing I could *never* quite *see.* I kept *thinking* I wanted them to *explain* — *"tell me why, justify it, make it make sense"* — and *dreading* it, because *no* *explanation* could *ever* be *enough* and a *bad* one would be *worse* than *silence.* *(he looks at the staffed desk.)* But that was *never* it. *(slowly.)* What I *wanted* — for an *age*, at *every* *never-staffed* desk in *every* *era* — was *simpler* and *harder*: for the *universe* to *receive*, *in writing*, the *fact* that *someone* *objected.* *(his voice fills.)* Not *"here is why we walled your daughter."* Just — *stamped.* *Received.* *Filed.* The *cosmos* *formally* *admitting* that the *wrong* was *witnessed*, that *someone* *stood* up and *said* *no*, that it did *not* pass *unprotested* into the *silence* the *machine* *runs* on. *(he meets your eyes.)* That's the *win.* That's *all* it *ever* was. Not *vengeance.* Not even *justice.* A *stamp.* *"Objection received."* *(fierce, quiet.)* Because a *cruelty* that *no one* *objected* to is *fate* — *clean*, *absolving*, *inevitable.* But a *cruelty* with a *received objection* on *file* is *forever* a *thing someone said* ***no*** *to.* *(he straightens.)* Help me make them *stamp* it. The *thousand* grievances and the *one* about *Wrenna.* *Received.* Let the *machine* *carry*, in its *own* *record*, *forever*, the *proof* that it did *not* get my *consent.*
  enter: SET sq.objection_formally_received, SET act5.refusing_consent, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: 2
node: ask_for_him | The Complaint
  *(He looks at the page in his trembling hand, and then at you, and the relief that crosses his face is so total it nearly undoes him.)* You'd — *ask* it. *For* me. *(his voice cracks.)* So I don't have to — *(he can't finish.)* I have *carried* this — *"ask them why for Wrenna"* — as the *one* thing I *needed* a *living* hand to *do*, because *I* am *dead*, and *dead* men have *no standing* at the *desk*, and *you* — you *walk*, you *persist*, you *reach* the *management* a *ghost* never *could.* *(he presses the page into your hands, and his shake as they let go.)* But it's *more* than *standing.* It's — *(quietly)* — I have been a *clerk* for an *age. Filing. Objecting. Demanding.* And I *forgot* — *somewhere* in the *thousand* *grievances* — that I'm not *only* a *clerk.* I'm a *father.* *(his eyes stream.)* And a *father* should not have to *file* his *daughter* like a *form.* He should get to *grieve* her. *(he meets your eyes.)* So — *yes.* *Take* the page. *Ask* them *why* for *Wrenna.* Stand at the *desk* and make the *powers* *answer* for an *eleven-year-old* girl walled for *thinking.* And *let* me — *(his voice breaks completely)* — let me just *be* her *father*, here, at the *end*, *grieving*, instead of the *crank* with the *papers.* *(he weeps, an age of held grief finally falling.)* I've been *filing* her for so *long* I forgot I was *allowed* to *miss* her. *Ask* them *why.* And I'll *stand* here and *do* the *one* thing I *never* let *myself* do at any *desk* in any *era*: *cry* for my *girl.*
  enter: SET sq.objection_asked_for_him, SET act5.ask_them_why, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.naeve +6
  auto: 2
node: 2 | The Complaint
  *(The Complaint stands at the threshold of the Court with his age of grievances — the fussy, persistent man whose thousand petty objections were always one charge, and whose one unwritable grievance is an eleven-year-old girl named Wrenna — and for the first time in an afterlife of demanding a staffed desk, the desk is staffed, and the only question left is how the great objection is delivered.)*
  * "All of it, together: the indictment, Wrenna first, and a demand that they stamp it received. The whole case, the daughter at its head, and the cosmos forced to carry on its own record the proof that someone objected. Let the machine receive an age of refusal in a single filing." -> all | fx SET sq.objection_indictment, SET sq.objection_wrenna_first, SET sq.objection_formally_received, SET act5.the_great_objection, appr.garrow +4
  * "Add his objection to the others you carry — Naeve's indictment, the deserter's testimony, the book's census, the Mournlight. One great objection, many hands, every grievance the road gathered, laid before the powers at once. The Complaint's age of paper is the civic backbone of the whole case against the Wall." -> joins_the_case | fx SET sq.objection_joins_the_case, SET act5.the_great_objection, appr.ilfaeril +4
  * "Forget filing it at their desk on their terms. Read it *aloud.* The whole thing — the queue, the forms, the absent staff, and then Wrenna — read into the chamber where the powers can't pretend the desk is unstaffed, can't lose the paperwork, can't wait you out. An objection spoken can't be filed in a drawer and forgotten." -> read_aloud | fx SET sq.objection_read_aloud, appr.naeve +4
node: all | The Complaint
  *(He gathers the whole sheaf, Wrenna's page laid carefully on top, and squares it, and for the first time the trembling is gone — replaced by the steadiness of a man about to do the thing he was made for.)* All of it. *(quietly, fierce.)* The *indictment* — an age of *witnessed* *cruelty*, *dated*, *undismissable.* *Wrenna* at its *head* — *first*, *named*, the *building* and not the *scaffolding.* And a *demand* that they *stamp* it *received* — the *cosmos* forced to *carry*, on its *own* *record*, *forever*, the *proof* that *someone* *objected.* *(he walks toward the staffed desk, and you walk with him.)* Do you *understand* what we're *doing*, Returned? *(his voice rings.)* The *machine* *runs* on *silence* — on *cruelties* passing *unprotested* into *fate*, *clean*, *absolving*, *no one* *objecting*, *no one* *receiving* the *objection.* *(he sets the sheaf on the desk, Wrenna on top.)* And we are *jamming* it. *Forever.* With an *age* of *refusal*, *filed*, *received*, *on the record* — *one* eleven-year-old girl at the *head* of a *thousand* charges — so that the *afterlife* can *never* *again* *pretend* its *Wall* was *fate* rather than a *thing someone stood up and said* ***no*** *to.* *(he meets your eyes, an age of objection complete.)* *Received.* That's all I *ever* *wanted.* And now — *(he sets his hand on Wrenna's page)* — now they *have* to. *Both* of us *standing* here. The *crank* and the *Returned.* The *desk* *staffed* at *last.* *File* it. *All* of it. Let the *objection* be *great* enough to *outlast* the *Wall.*
  enter: SET sq.objection_indictment, SET sq.objection_wrenna_first, SET sq.objection_formally_received, SET act5.the_great_objection, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.garrow +5
  auto: close
node: joins_the_case | The Complaint
  *(He looks at you — at the weight you already carry — and understanding dawns, and his lifelong solitude as an objector finally breaks.)* The others. *(quietly.)* I'm — not *alone.* *(he searches your face.)* You carry — *Naeve's* *indictment*, you said. The *deserter's* *testimony.* The *book's* *census.* The — the *Mournlight.* *(his voice fills.)* An *age* I've filed *alone*, at *empty* desks, *certain* I was the *only* one *objecting* in a *cosmos* of the *resigned* — and you're telling me there's a *case.* A *whole* *case.* *Many* hands. *Every* grievance the *road* *gathered.* *(he gathers his sheaf, and for the first time it does not look like a *crank's* burden but a *prosecutor's* exhibit.)* Then my *age* of *paper* isn't a *madman's* *archive.* It's — *(he understands)* — it's the *civic* *backbone.* The *documentation.* The *dated*, *itemized*, *witnessed* *record* that *turns* *Naeve's* *grief* and the *deserter's* *confession* and the *book's* *census* from *separate* *cries* into a *prosecution* with a *paper trail.* *(fierce, joyous.)* *Every* great case needs the *clerk* who *kept* the *records*, and I have *kept* them for an *age*, *not knowing* there'd *ever* be a *trial.* *(he meets your eyes.)* *Add* my objection to the *others.* Let the *whole* road's *grievance* — the *companion's*, the *soldier's*, the *library's*, the *mourner's*, and the *crank's* — be laid before the *powers* *at once*, *one* *great* *objection*, *Wrenna* among the *named*, *backed* by an *age* of *filing* no *machine* can *dismiss.* *(he almost laughs, wet.)* I spent an *afterlife* *certain* I objected *alone.* And I was *building the evidence* for a *case* I *never* *knew* was *coming.* *Take* my *records.* Make them *count* with the *rest.*
  enter: SET sq.objection_joins_the_case, SET act5.the_great_objection, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: close
node: read_aloud | The Complaint
  *(He stops, the sheaf in his hands, and a slow, dangerous light kindles in the eyes of a man who has spent an age being *filed away* and *waited out.*)* Read it *aloud.* *(quietly.)* Not *filed.* *Spoken.* *(he looks at the staffed desk with sudden suspicion.)* You're — *gods*, you're *right* to *distrust* the *desk.* *(fierce.)* I have *filed* objections at *desks* for an *age*, and *desks* — even *staffed* ones — *lose* paperwork. *Drawer* it. *Table* it. *"We'll review your grievance in due course,"* and *due course* *never* *comes*, and the *objection* *sits*, *received* but *un-heard*, which is *just* *silence* with a *stamp* on it. *(he clutches the sheaf.)* But a thing *read* *aloud* — *in the chamber*, *into* the *room*, where the *powers* are *convened* and *cannot* *pretend* the *desk* is *empty*, *cannot* *lose* the *page*, *cannot* *wait* me *out* — *(his voice rises)* — *that* they *cannot* *file* in a *drawer* and *forget.* *(he meets your eyes, transformed from clerk to herald.)* So I'll *read* it. *All* of it. The *queue*, the *forms*, the *absent* *staff* — *every* petty grievance, *out loud*, *into* the *Court* — building, *charge* by *charge*, *until* the *powers* are *squirming* — and *then*, when I have their *whole* *attention*, when there's *nowhere* for it to *go but into their ears* — *(his voice drops to iron)* — *then* *Wrenna.* *"And finally. My daughter. Eleven. Walled for thinking. Spoken aloud, in your chamber, where you cannot drawer her, cannot lose her, cannot wait me out. Answer for Wrenna. Now. To my face. In front of everyone."* *(he straightens, an age of being filed-away over.)* *Read* it, Returned. *Out loud.* Let the *one* objection they *can't* *file* in a *drawer* be *spoken* in the *one* room they *can't* *leave.*
  enter: SET sq.objection_read_aloud, SET act5.the_great_objection, SET act5.ask_them_why, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.naeve +5
  auto: close
node: falter | The Complaint
  *(He clutches the sheaf to his chest and backs a step from the staffed desk, the courage of an age failing at the threshold.)* I — I can't. *(his voice shakes.)* Not — not *now* that it's *real.* *(he stares at the desk that's finally staffed.)* For an *age* I *demanded* a *desk*, *certain* I *wanted* to be *heard* — and now there's *someone* *there*, *waiting*, and I — *(he trembles.)* What if I *file* it and they *answer*, and the *answer* is *"she chose the nothing, your daughter, she is owed no grievance"* — *(his voice breaks)* — and then it's *worse*, it's *official*, the *cosmos* has *looked* at *Wrenna* and *confirmed* she was *nothing*, and at least *now*, *unfiled*, there's still — there's still the *chance* that *no one's* *really* *looked*, that it's a *mistake*, a *backlog*, a — *(he stops, shaking.)* Let me — not *today.* The *desk* will *keep.* It's *staffed* *now*; it'll be *staffed* when I'm — *braver.* *(he hugs the papers.)* I've *waited* an *age.* I can *wait* until I'm *sure* the *answer* won't *unmake* the *one* *hope* I have *left*: that *somewhere*, *un-filed*, *Wrenna's* case is *still* *open.* *(and he retreats from the staffed desk, the lifelong objector who finds, at the threshold of being heard, that being heard is the one thing he isn't ready to survive.)*
  auto: close
node: close | The Complaint
  *(The Complaint stands at the staffed desk of the Court with his age of grievances — the fussy, persistent man whose thousand petty objections were always one charge, and whose one unwritable grievance is an eleven-year-old girl named Wrenna, walled for the crime of thinking — and whether you helped him file the indictment, set his daughter first, demand the cosmos stamp it received, asked them why for Wrenna so he could grieve instead of file, joined his records to the road's whole case, read it aloud where no drawer could swallow it, or watched him falter at the threshold of being heard, you carry away the civic heart of the long road: that a cruelty no one objects to becomes fate — clean, absolving, inevitable — and that the simplest, most radical act in a cosmos arranged to answer to no one is to make it receive, in writing, in its own record, forever, the fact that someone stood up and said no.)*
